<br>
&quot;Hey, where is everyone?&quot; I said to myself as I looked around to find noone near me. &quot;And where am I? I am certainly not in Cobalt Scars.&quot;<br>
<br>
I studied my surroundings intently. I sniffed the gentile breeze, noticing the moisture in the air, yet a certain dryness to it. I look around the surrounding druid ruins, which are quite familliar to me, yet can't place at the monent. I look intently at the ground, and through the blades of bright green grass, I noticed a small pile of sand.<br>
<br>
&quot;So, I am in the southern desert of Ro. Why am I here instead of in Cobalt?&quot; I again asked myself. Certainly, the teleportation spell couldn't have sent one person to the wrong place and not everyone else. How odd.<br>
<br>
I sat down into the lush grass for a minute to regather my thoughts. &quot;I doubt that they will be able to find me here, so I will gate back to the Nexus.&quot; I grasp hold of my spellbook, which is always tucked away safely inside a pocket of my robe. I open the book to the first page. Looking down through the numerous words foreign to many across Norrath, I found the particular spell line I was looking for. These words I committed to memory, making sure I knew the proper fluctuations, pitch, and frequency.<br>
<br>
I put my spellbook back inside my robe and stood up. Sounds began to flow from my mouth. My skin began to burn as the magic I was born with began to erupt and fill me with an exstacy only magic can give. Faster and faster, the sounds came. Light began to converge around me, slowly growing brighter, until it was blinding. The last word of the spell exited from my lips. The light faded away and.....<br>
<br>
&quot;What's going on?&quot; I yelled as I came to realize I am still in Ro. A startled wolf pup let out a yip and ran off into some nearby bushes, waiting for his mother to return. The gate spell, able to be learned by many classes at a very early age, almost never fails, unless one's concentration is less than perfect. My concentration was just fine though!<br>
<br>
After regaining my scomposure and the strength wasted away from the casting of the spell, I attempted it again. Still nothing. I attempted again after a few minutes. Yet again, nothing. After about the 10th time, I gave up.<br>
<br>
&quot;What is going on here&quot; I thought to myself. What could possibly not allow my gate spell to work? Am I doing something wrong? Did I memorize the spell wrong? Am I losing the magic that is my life? I knew in my heart that the last three thoughts were all the same answer: No. I have cast this spell an uncountable number of times, and what I did now was no different than the first time I successfully cast it. Then what could possibly be preventing me from leaving here?<br>
<br>
*Thump*<br>
<br>
&quot;OW!&quot; I screamed, as a wooden club bounced off my head. I quickly stood up and turned around to face an orc warrior, who thought I would be easy prey.<br>
<br>
&quot;Orc stomp, orc kill. Orc weapons, your blood will spill!&quot; the brutish orc yelled in a wild battlecry. Foam frothed from his mouth and his eyes bulged out of his head.<br>
<br>
Anger rose from within me and boiled over into the fire. &quot;I'll teach you what happens when you fool around with the wrong person, foolish Orc.&quot; The orc swong a valliant blow, which sailed over my head. The magic from deep within began to fester and swell. Words of magic poured from my mouth like water coming out of a faucet. A reddish glow eminated from my skin as the air around prickled in the magic.<br>
<br>
The orc landed another blow to my right shoulder, a mere scratch it left. From my many years of training, I have learned to focus on the magic and not allow myself to be distracted. This orc will not disrupt me. I threw out my hands toward the orc. A huge ball of fire shot out from my fingertips and smote the orc square in the chest. The smell of charred orc flesh hung heavy in the air as the orc fell dead at my feet. <br>
<br>
After a quick inspection of the pockets of the orc, I left him and his smoldering club to rot away until the wolves picked the meat off his bones. My feet drove me northward through the Ro Desert, in search of the reason why I have arrived here.<br>
