<br>
&quot;Hail, gnome.&quot; a scruffy looking, well muscled human said mildly. &quot;What brings you to these parts?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I am Jimbop of Akanon, and will not be addressed as 'gnome.'  I am a friend of this city and demand to be allowed to pass.&quot;<br>
<br>
A look of impatience flashed upon the veteran's face. &quot;Yes, yes. I have heard of you. You are allowed admittance to the city.&quot; The other guard glanced over in suspision.<br>
<br>
&quot;Ok, thank you.&quot; I said briefly as I began to walk past, slightly annoyed for being unable to finish my introduction. I got about three steps past the guards when I whirled around to ask a quick question. The other guard dropped his hand to his sword.<br>
<br>
&quot;By the way, has anything strange been going on lately?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;What do you mean, gno....I mean Jimbop.&quot; the veteran corrected himself, knowing that gnomes are offended when referred to as 'gnome.'<br>
<br>
&quot;I tried casting my self transportation spell, but it wouldn't work. Have any travellers of late complained about this?&quot;<br>
<br>
A puzzled look came across both the guards' faces. The other guard spoke for the first time in a deep raspy voice, &quot;We have not heard anything of this. We are only guards, who have no use for magic. Maybe you should go to the magic-wielders guild.&quot; A brief, almost inaudible sentence came from his voice as I began to turn around to leave.<br>
<br>
&quot;Thank you. I will do just that.&quot; I walked swiftly away from the two guards, not trusting neither one, especially the guard who mentioned that I should go back to the magic-wielders guild in Ak'anon where I belong.<br>
<br>
My path took me past numerous stone and wooden buildings. A creaking sign swayed in the breeze in front of a rowdy bar. A street vendor swatted the hand of a snooping street urchin. An elf stood in front of a blacksmith, negotiating the price of a finely polished blade of very high quality with it's human owner. And all the while, the smell of the sea hung heavy in the overcast sky.<br>
<br>
I glanced up to find the sun's position to find the day is in the waning hours. &quot;I shall try to take the portal to the Plane of Knowledge, for it's magic should not be failing.&quot; I thought to myself while stepping aside to avoid a pleasantly drunk dwarf staggering in the street babbling something about the bar being on fire.<br>
<br>
After about twenty minutes of walking, I arrived to another gate, almost exactly identical to the gate I came in at, only here many more guards were posted. The town militia building stood just inside the gates to this entrance. Heavy armor-clad humans with gleaming longswords bustled about, protecting the populance from thieves, murderers, and the occasional invader. Like the other gate, two guards stood on duty to protect the gate, and to assure no intruders are allowed entrance.<br>
<br>
With my mind on other thoughts, I paid no heed to the guards. &quot;What could possibly cause teleportation not to work? Did the same thing happen to my group? Are they still stuck in the Nexus or.....&quot;<br>
<br>
As if rousing out of a deep slumber, I came to the realization I was being spoken to.<br>
<br>
&quot;Hey Gnome!&quot; A rough looking human with a chest and arms bulgiong out of his armor spoke to me.<br>
<br>
&quot;I am Jimbop of Akanon, and do not.......&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Yes, I know you are. I just wanted to let you know to be wary of travelling. Very few visitors have come by today, which is very odd for this time of year. I fear there may be danger on the paths ahead.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I fear no danger, Sir. I will be fine, but thank you for your warning.&quot; With a quick bow, I followed the left wall. I continued to follow this until I came to one stretch, and I stopped. Looking at this wall, it seemed ordinary. Every stone looked the same, and looked to be masterfully built. I lifted up my hand and tried to touch the wall, only my hand became part of the wall. I drew myself into the wall, and walked through the illusion. &quot;I always hated trying to find this place&quot; I thought briefly.<br>
<br>
I emerged into a tunnel burrowing underneath the city of Freeport. Underground is how the evil travel throughout Freeport. Seeing noone around at this time, I proceeded in, my soft padded shoes kicking up dirt along the way. A faint red glow partially illuminated the hallway. The walls were roughly cut and looked to be dug out in a hurry. A trickle of water ran down and collected in a small pool. Then a faint blue glow began to emerge in the darkness. After rounding a small corner, I came to stand in front of an ancient book on a pedastal.<br>
<br>
Magic flowed forth from this ancient tome, touching every soul and filling him or her with the ability to cast a magic spell, even if he has never casted a spell before. In it's crisp pages contain one single spell, the ability to translocate yourself to the Plane of Knowledge. My steps took me up to the tome, it's power mingling with my blood. I open up the book and memorize the words needed to cast the spell. After a minute, I gently close the book and take a step back.<br>
<br>
Spell fresh in mind, I begin to recite the incantation. My arms flutter up in response to the words of the song. My magic twined with the magic of the tome and flared like wildfire in my body. Exstacy filled my mind and magical balls swirled around me. I closed my eyes and saw visions of the beauty of Knowledge, the radiant skies, the crisp clean air, the birds in the trees. I could see all races in existance living in complete harmony with one another. I could see travellers abroad in search of endless adventures. I could see many vendors selling almost anything you could possibly want. Most of all, I could see the gleaming white castle standing proudly in the center of the land. I opened my eyes to take in all these wonderful sights. The first thing I noticed was....<br>
<br>
The bluish-tinted tunnel wall.<br>
