<br>
My hand draped around the crystal. n inaudible whisper seeped from my lips. The once ordinary necklace came alive with brilliance. Shimmering blue light eminated from the cracks between my gnarled fingers, illuminating my red robe with its intensity. Darkness fled in fear from the intruding light, disappearing behind any rock or crevice it could find. A nearby rat, frightened by the change in her home, scurried away in search of the blessed cover of darkness.<br>
<br>
Images of my guild hall filled my vision. Oak tables sat in line with many chairs resting underneath them. Long benches ran along the walls covered in tapestries depicting events that transpired in the history of the Knights. On the back wall stood the grand tapestry that proudly displayed the guild name to all who entered the magnificent hall. Voices of familliar faces streamed into my ears, yet no faces graced my vision of the hall. With the magic of the crystal broadcasting strong, I gathered up my thoughts and began to speak to the members of my guild.<br>
<br>
&quot;I have a question to ask of everyone. Has anyone noticed anything weird going on today like not being able to teleport or gate?&quot;<br>
<br>
A chorus of &quot;No&quot; and &quot;No Jim&quot; answers reverberated off from the walls. Despair began to fill my mind when one lone voice rose up and offered me a question in return.<br>
<br>
&quot;Why, what's wrong Jim?&quot; a strong and determined feminine voice asked. Quickly, I was able to put a face to this voice that imposed an unrealized tone of authority.<br>
<br>
&quot;I'm not sure Mysty.&quot; I said to Mystykal, the leader of the Nomadic Knights. &quot;I was with a group of my friends when we ported out to Cobalt Scars. When the spell was finished, I lost all contact with my friends and ended up in the Desert of Ro. I tried to gate back to PoK, but the gate spell wouldn't work. I ran over to the PoK portal outside of Freeport, but it also won't work. Now I am stuck here, unable to contact my friends. Does anyone know what could be going on?&quot;<br>
<br>
Silence answered me.<br>
<br>
&quot;Anyone?&quot; I again asked.<br>
<br>
A deep human voice answered me, which belonged to Gruven Tothebeat, tank extrordinaire. &quot;I don't know Jim. Maybe you just need a quick nap to clear your brain. Sometimes after being awake a while, your mind doesn't remember stuff right.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;That's not all I have to say either.&quot; I stated. &quot;When I was in Freeport, the guards seemed very worried. Travel has come to a standstill. No trade has come in or out. No travellers have come in or out. Nothing. They seem to think something in the land is strange.&quot;<br>
<br>
The voice of Erki, the appointed leader of magic, was the next voice to be heard. &quot;Very odd. So far, I have had no troubles out here in Velious. Maybe you are just letting yourself get distracted while casting your spells. It happens to the best of us.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;But that doesn't explain why the guards are suspicious and why travel has dropped off.&quot; I replied. &quot;And, more importantly, that doesn't explain why I ended up in Ro instead of with my group in Cobalt.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Maybe your group was trying to tell you something by dropping you off in Ro, Jim.&quot; said another voice.<br>
<br>
&quot;Maybe they thought you were gonna fall asleep again during the teleport or randomly during a battle, like before.&quot; Erki stated.<br>
<br>
&quot;Very funny Eyan and Erki.&quot; I said with a sneer. &quot;Seriously though, does anyone know what could be going on?&quot;<br>
<br>
A few no's were heard, and that was about it. Frustrated about not knowing what is going on, I told everyone that I was going to take a small nap and go from there. After saying my goodbyes, I let go of the crystal. The crystal held it's brilliance for a few seconds, and slowly it died back down into the indistinct crystal it once was.<br>
<br>
I walked outside of the tunnel and headed over to the Freeport entrance. A few beetles skittered across the sand in front of me, and a bat flew sightlessly through the dimming sky. I reached the entrance to Freeport and walked through without acknowledging the guards, yet I noticed the main guard breathed a sigh of relief, for he would not have to possibly clean up someone's corpse the next day.<br>
<br>
I sat down not far from the entrance and leaned my back against the stone wall of the city. I reached into my backpack and pulled out a piece of bread and a water flask. I silently ate the bread and washed it down with the water and let my thoughts flow.<br>
<br>
&quot;Will everything be ok when I wake up? Am I just letting myself become distracted? And will that nagging pain in my foot go away? Ugh!&quot;<br>
<br>
I pulled my knees up to my chest and folded my arms across them and leaned my head into them. Within a few minutes, the guards were able to hear how loud a gnome can snore.<br>
